mostly short, serious illnesses and disabilities were common at every age, and dying was quick. Today, most Americans live a long life, with the disabilities and discomforts of progressive chronic illness appearing only during the final chapters of their life stories. Sick to Death and Not Going to Take It Anymore! maintains that health care and community services are not set up to meet the needs of the large number of people who face a prolonged period of progressive illness and disability before death. Lynn offers what she calls an "owner's manual for the health care system," which lays out facts, concepts, strategies, and action plans for genuine reform and gives the reader new ways to interpret information creatively, imagine innovative possibilities, and take steps to implement them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChronically illxMedical carezUnited States. 0aHealth care reformzUnited States. 0aOlder peoplexLong-term carezUnited States. 0aOlder peoplexMedical carezUnited States. 0aTerminal carezUnited States. 7aMEDICAL / Health Care Delivery.2bisacsh  aadvance care planning.  aaging.  aalzheimers.  aamerican hospital association.  aat home care.  ababy boomers.  acaregivers.  achronic illness.  adegenerative disease.  adementia.  adisability.  adisease.  agerontology.  ahealth and wellness.  ahealth care delivery.  ahealth care reform.  ahealth care.  ahealth policy.  ahospice.  ahospitals.  aillness.  alife span.  along term care.  amedicine.  amodern health care.  anonfiction.  anursing home.  apalliative care.  aprogressive illness.  aretirement home.  aseniors.  aterminal care.1 aBerwick, Donald M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu